#Text=Sallie Mae leads Consumer Financial Protection Bureau complaints about student loans
#Text=Tuesday , October 1 , 2013
#Text=File photo of Sallie Mae 's headquarters in 2007
#Text=Image : Joshua Davis .

#Text=A review this week by Wikinews of US Consumer Financial Protection Bureau ( CFPB ) complaints about student loans in the United States shows Sallie Mae leads all lending institutions in complaints .
#Text=Of the 4,851 complaints dating back to March 2012 when the CFPB first began collecting student loan data , 2,262 or 46.6 % of all complaints were about the lender .
#Text=US Federal Reserve data from 2010/2011 shows Sallie Mae is the nation 's largest student loan lender , responsible for 25 % of the market
#Text=The other major lenders in this space include Wells Fargo , JP Morgan Chase , PNC , and Discover .
#Text=In complaints , AES / PHEAA came in second with 546 , or 11.3 % of all complaints .
#Text=Wells Fargo , Citibank and JPMorgan Chase each had between 5 % and 7.5 % of all complaints , totaling 918 complaints between them .
#Text=78 other lending institutions round out the list of organizations with complaints filed against them for student loans .
#Text=Few of the complaints originate from people with problems with federal student loans .
#Text=Less than 1 % , 35 total , are for these types of loans , with Sallie Mae accounting for the bulk of complaints with 17 total .
#Text=14 other lending institutions have 3 or fewer complaints .
#Text=For non-federal student loans , Sallie Mae is still the leader for complaints , with 2245 or 46.6 % of all non-federal student loan complaints .
#Text=The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau sorts complaints into three issues :
#Text=Problems when you are unable to pay , Repaying your loan , and Getting a loan .
#Text=None of the federal loans had complaints about getting a loan .
#Text=For non-federal loans , 65.5 % of the 4,816 complaints related to loan repayment .
#Text=Sallie Mae led in total complaints in this category with 1467 .
#Text=They were followed by AES/PHEAA with 356 , Wells Fargo with 231 , Citibank with 201 , Discover with 158 , JPMorgan Chase with 154 , ACS Education Services with 143 , and KeyBank NA with 116 .
#Text=CFPB says loan repayment issues include a basket of claim types including " fees , billing , deferment , forbearance , fraud , and credit reporting . "
#Text=Problems when you are unable pay accounts for 30.8 % of the complaints .
#Text=Sallie Mae had 698 complaints .
#Text=They were followed by AES/PHEAA with 181 , JPMorgan Chase with 106 , Wells Fargo with 104 , Citibank with 70 , and KeyBank NA with 58 .
#Text=Many of the complaints are , according to the CFPB , because borrowers have difficulty getting deferrments on loan repayment as a result of being unable to find employment .
#Text=Month by month complaints against major lenders
#Text=Image : Laura Hale .
#Text=The total complaints against Sallie Mae for September of this year is 2 fewer than the same time last year .
#Text=The company 's performance this year compared to last year has been mixed .
#Text=March and June numbers were down over 150 complaints from the same month a year before .
#Text=April , May , July and August all saw increases of 17 – 43 .
#Text=Of the top six lenders by volume of complaints , only AES/PHEAA and Citibank saw drops every month between March and September from the total volume in the previous year .
#Text=Wells Fargo had a gain of 1 in August and 6 in May from the previous year .
#Text=JPMorgan Chase had a difference of 0 from the same month last year for April , 3 more this year for May , and 4 more for August .
#Text=Discover saw an increase every month from the same period last year except for September .
#Text=When the total complaints differences from year to year for March to September are counted , this year has 571 fewer complaints against the top six lenders .
#Text=Closure reason
#Text=percentage for student loan complaints by lender
#Text=Image : Laura Hale .
#Text=Most , 1470 , of the complaints against Sallie Mae were closed with explanations .
#Text=10.2 % were closed with monetary relief .
#Text=7.7 % were closed with non-monetary relief .
#Text=2.1 % were closed with relief and 12.1 % were closed without relief .
#Text=AES/PHEAA 's complaint closure picture was much different .
#Text=40.1 % of AES/PHEAA 's 546 complaints were closed with non-monetary relief , 35.3 % were closed with explanations and 21.2 % were closed without relief .

#Text=Of the eight lending institutions with 100 or more complaints filed against them , Discover was the institution most likely to result in a closure with monetary relief with 12.9 % of all their closures ending this way .
#Text=Citibank was the institution with the highest percentage of closures ending with no relief at 26.0 % .
#Text=Geographic distribution of student loan complaints
#Text=Image : Laura Hale .
#Text=Complaints over student loan lenders were geographically distributed , coming from 3,447 different zip codes .
#Text=The largest cluster of complaints is for 20001 , a Washington D.C. zip code with 10 complaints originating from there .
#Text=07950 , the zip code for Morris Plains , New Jersey , and 37013 , the zip code for Antioch , Tennessee , each had 8 complaints originating from them .
#Text=Zip codes for Patchogue , New York ; Philadelphia , Pennsylvania ; Washington D.C. ; and Arlington , Virginia each had 7 complaints originating from them .
#Text=By volume of complaints by state , New York led with 497 , with California second with 467 , Pennsylvania third with 303 , Florida fourth with 288 and Ohio fifth with 219 complaints .
#Text=US Territories largely occupied the bottom spots .
#Text=The Northern Marianas Islands , with a population of around 50,000 , had 1 complaint .
#Text=The U.S. Armed Forces – Pacific had 3 .
#Text=North Dakota and U.S. Armed Forces – Europe had 5 complaints each .
#Text=South Dakota had 7 .
#Text=Wyoming had 8 .
#Text=Puerto Rico and Alaska had 9 each .
#Text=Rounding out the bottom five states by volume of complaints , Mississippi had 11 .
#Text=With the possibility of a United States government federal shutdown looming on October 1 , student loans may be impacted because of potential for an automatic increase in interest rates .
